{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"12b37e76-f933-4fc6-9d0b-7096bd7ce9a4","content":"**`AddScoped` doesn't work the same way in MAUI as in ASP.NET Core.**\n\nIn ASP.NET Core, a \"scope\" is an HTTP request — each request gets a fresh `DbContext`. In MAUI, there are no HTTP requests, so **there is no natural scope boundary**. The DI container never creates a new scope, meaning `AddScoped` effectively behaves like `AddSingleton`. Your `DbContext` lives for the entire app lifetime, accumulating tracked entities across navigations.\n\n**Fixes:**\n\n1. **Use `AddTransient`** — a new `DbContext` per injection:\n   ```csharp\n   builder.Services.AddTransient<MyDbContext>();\n   ```\n\n2. **Or inject `IServiceScopeFactory` and manage scopes manually:**\n   ```csharp\n   using var scope = scopeFactory.CreateScope();\n   var db = scope.ServiceProvider.GetRequiredService<MyDbContext>();\n   ```\n\n3. **Or clear the change tracker** when navigating:\n   ```csharp\n   dbContext.ChangeTracker.Clear();\n   ```\n\n`AddTransient` is the simplest drop-in fix for most cases.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"99460f71-a981-4113-833a-443c38ccde85","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a common pitfall when moving from ASP.NET Core to .NET MAUI regarding dependency injection scoping, specifically with `AddScoped` and `DbContext`. This is a conceptual question I can answer directly without needing to search any codebase.\n\nThe key issue: In ASP.NET Core, `AddScoped` creates a new instance per HTTP request. In MAUI, there's no concept of an HTTP request scope — the app is a single long-running process. So `AddScoped` effectively behaves like `AddSingleton`, meaning the same `DbContext` instance is reused for the entire app lifetime.","outputTokens":443,"requestId":"1423:1287AC:6F3A197:779193B:6A03CE9E"},"id":"9a590a60-cc80-4472-a0cb-0432f113f052","timestamp":"2026-05-13T01:06:49.109Z","parentId":"74be41b0-f6da-4801-80c5-99c430660d11"}
